The paper deals with algorithms for preference aggregation, which is a topic that falls under the umbrella of artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The algorithms are evaluated on real-life and synthetic data, which suggests that the paper could also be categorized under data structures and algorithms (cs.DS). The paper also discusses the Chamberlin-Courant and Monroe rules, which are concepts in game theory (cs.GT). The evaluation of the algorithms involves measuring the quality of the solutions, which could be considered a machine learning task (cs.LG). Finally, the paper deals with the practical implementation of the algorithms, which could be categorized under social and information networks (cs.SI).
